 12  /-!
 13  # The category of commutative rings has all limits
 14  
 15  Further, these limits are preserved by the forgetful functor --- that is,
 16  the underlying types are just the limits in the category of types.
 17  
 18  ## Further work
 19  A lot of this should be generalised / automated, as it's quite common for concrete
 20  categories that the forgetful functor preserves limits.
 21  -/
 22  
 23  open category_theory
 24  open category_theory.limits

 97  namespace CommRing_has_limits
 98  -- The next two definitions are used in the construction of `has_limits CommRing`.
 99  -- After that, the limits should be constructed using the generic limits API,
100  -- e.g. `limit F`, `limit.cone F`, and `limit.is_limit F`.
101  
102  /--
103  Construction of a limit cone in `CommRing`.
104  (Internal use only; use the limits API.)
105  -/
106  def limit (F : J ⥤ CommRing.{u}) : cone F :=
id                  ┴ ┴ └──────┘        └──┘ ┴

txt                                   └────────────┘

109    { app := λ j, ring_hom.of $ limit.π (F ⋙ forget _) j,
